This paper is likely to belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category as it focuses on implementing and evaluating correlated noise models in deep convolutional neural networks. The paper also discusses the impact of correlated variability on the classification of occluded and non-occluded images, which is a common task in computer vision, suggesting that it may also belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of regularization techniques such as dropout, which is a common topic in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of differentiable procedures, which is a common topic in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the impact of correlations on cortical processing, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category.
